library(tidyverse)
library(tidymodels)
# load your data 
MArea <- read_csv("data/HDM_CouncilArea.csv")

CouncilArea <- read_csv("data/CouncilArea.csv")
## Rows: 44 Columns: 14
##  Column specification 
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (7): CA, CAName, HSCP, HSCPName, HB, HBName, Country
## dbl (7): _id, CADateEnacted, CADateArchived, HSCPDateEnacted, HSCPDateArchiv...
## 
##  Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
##  Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
Data<- MArea %>%
  select(Year,CA,AgeGroup,Sex,Diagnosis,CrudeRate,EASR) %>%
  drop_na()
#Question - How does the crude rate for heart diseases compare between regions in Scotland?
#Chart of Area

Regions <- CouncilArea %>%
  mutate(
    Region = case_when(
      CA %in% c("S12000033", "S12000034", "S12000020", "S12000017") ~ "North",
      CA %in% c("S12000038", "S12000039", "S12000015") ~ "North East",
      CA %in% c("S12000005", "S12000014", "S12000026", "S12000036", "S12000042", "S12000044") ~ "Central",
      CA %in% c("S12000006", "S12000010", "S12000019", "S12000028", "S12000045") ~ "South",
      CA %in% c("S12000008", "S12000009", "S12000011", "S12000018", "S12000021", "S12000023", "S12000027", "S12000030", "S12000035", "S12000040", "S12000041") ~ "West",
      CA %in% c("S92000003") ~ "Scotland",
      TRUE ~ "Others"
      )
  )

CA_joined <- left_join(MArea, Regions %>% select(CA, Region), by = "CA")
## Warning in left_join(MArea, Regions %>% select(CA, Region), by = "CA"): Detected an unexpected many-to-many relationship between `x` and `y`.
##  Row 41 of `x` matches multiple rows in `y`.
##  Row 1 of `y` matches multiple rows in `x`.
##  If a many-to-many relationship is expected, set `relationship =
##   "many-to-many"` to silence this warning.
CA_summary <- CA_joined %>%
  group_by(Region) %>%
  summarise(
    mean_deaths = mean(NumberOfDeaths, na.rm = TRUE),
    mean_rate  = mean(CrudeRate, na.rm = TRUE)
  )


  ggplot(CA_summary, aes(x = Region, y = mean_rate)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(
    title = "Crude Mortality Rate by Council Area",
    x = "Region",
    y = "Mean Crude Mortality Rate (%)"
  )

# Chart of EASR

ggplot(data = Data,
       mapping = aes(x = EASR, 
                     y = CrudeRate, 
                     )) +
  geom_point(size = 1)+
  geom_smooth(method = lm , se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

# Bar chart of Sex
table_sex<-Data %>%
  group_by(Sex) %>%
  summarise(mean_cruderate = mean(CrudeRate , na.rm = TRUE),
            median_cruderate = median(CrudeRate , na.rm = TRUE))

ggplot(table_sex)+
       geom_bar(mapping= aes (x=Sex,
                     y=mean_cruderate,
                     fill=Sex),
                     stat = "identity")+
  labs(title = "The mean value of cruderate for different Sexs",
       x="Sex",
       y="Mean Cruderate",
       fill="Sex")

#Bar chart of gender
table_age<-Data %>%
  group_by(AgeGroup) %>%
  summarise(mean_cruderate = mean(CrudeRate , na.rm = TRUE),
            median_cruderate = median(CrudeRate , na.rm = TRUE))%>%
  mutate(AgeGroup = fct_relevel(AgeGroup, "All" ,after = 0))

ggplot(table_age)+
       geom_bar(mapping= aes (x=AgeGroup,
                              y=mean_cruderate,
                              fill=AgeGroup),
                              stat = "identity")+
  labs(title = "The mean value of cruderate for different AgeGroups",
       x="Age",
       y="Mean Cruderate",
       fill="AgeGroup")

#Table 3 (Agegroup and Diagnosis)
Table_3<- Data %>%
  group_by(AgeGroup,Diagnosis) %>%
  summarise(mean_cruderate = mean(CrudeRate , na.rm = TRUE),
            median_cruderate = median(CrudeRate , na.rm = TRUE))%>%
  mutate(AgeGroup = fct_relevel(AgeGroup, "All" ,after = 0))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'AgeGroup'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
## Warning: There were 5 warnings in `mutate()`.
## The first warning was:
